7. Recommended Execution Order
The prompts should be executed in the following order to avoid conflicts and ensure each step builds on the previous one correctly. Each prompt is independent enough to be run as a separate Windsurf session, but the order matters for consistency.
1. Prompt 1 (Missing Translation Keys) — Run FIRST. This fills in all gaps in the existing JSON message files. Estimated effort: Medium. This is the most straightforward task with the least risk of breaking things.
2. Prompt 2 (Hardcoded Strings) — Run SECOND. This requires adding new keys to en.json and all language files, then modifying source code. The keys added in Prompt 1 are already in place, so you only need to add the NEW keys for previously-hardcoded strings. Estimated effort: Large. This touches many files across the project.
3. Prompt 3 (Data Files) — Run THIRD. This is the most architecturally significant change. It requires restructuring how data files work, adding large amounts of translation content, and updating all consuming components. Estimated effort: Very Large. Consider breaking this into sub-prompts per data file.
4. Prompt 4 (Quality Audit) — Run LAST. This verifies everything is correct and catches any remaining issues. Estimated effort: Medium.

7.1 Sub-Prompt Strategy for Data Files
Prompt 3 is extremely large. If Windsurf struggles with it, break it into these sub-prompts executed in sequence:
•  Sub-prompt 3a: Internationalize src/data/site-config.ts only
•  Sub-prompt 3b: Internationalize src/data/treatments.ts and src/data/treatment-collections.ts
•  Sub-prompt 3c: Internationalize src/data/conditions.ts
•  Sub-prompt 3d: Internationalize src/data/media.ts, src/data/testimonials.ts, and src/data/blog.ts
•  Sub-prompt 3e: Internationalize src/data/navigation.ts and src/data/homepage.ts
8. Language-Specific Translation Notes
These notes should be included in or referenced by each prompt to ensure translation quality across all target languages.
8.1 Arabic (ar)
•  RTL language — ensure text direction is properly handled in all components
•  Use Modern Standard Arabic (MSA/\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064A\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0635\u062D\u0649), not dialectal Arabic
•  Aesthetic/medical terminology should use accepted Arabic medical terms
•  Brand names (Silk Beauty Salon, Allergan, Juvederm, Galderma, Restylane, Merz) stay in English/Latin script
•  Personal names stay in their original form
•  The ₾ (Georgian Lari) symbol should be kept as-is or written as \u0644\u064A\u0631\u064A \u062C\u0648\u0631\u062C\u064A in context
8.2 Hebrew (he)
•  RTL language — same RTL considerations as Arabic
•  Use formal/modern Hebrew, not biblical or slang
•  Medical/aesthetic terminology often uses borrowed English terms with Hebrew spelling — follow industry convention
•  Brand names stay in English/Latin script
•  Place names: Batumi = \u05D1\u05D0\u05EA\u05D5\u05DE\u05D9, Georgia = \u05D2\u05D0\u05D5\u05E8\u05D2\u05D9\u05D4
8.3 Georgian (ka)
•  LTR language using unique Georgian alphabet (Mkhedruli script)
•  Do NOT use Russian/Cyrillic characters for Georgian translations
•  Georgian has its own medical terminology — use established Georgian medical terms
•  Some international terms (like Botox, Hydrafacial) are commonly used in their English form in Georgian aesthetic context
•  Georgian names (Nino, Ketevan, Mariam, Sophia) stay in Georgian script: \u10DC\u10D8\u10DC\u10DD, \u10E5\u10D4\u10D7\u10D4\u10D5\u10D0\u10DC\u10D8, \u10DB\u10D0\u10E0\u10D8\u10D0\u10DB\u10D8, \u10E1\u10DD\u10E4\u10D8\u10D0
8.4 Russian (ru)
•  LTR language using Cyrillic script
•  Use standard Russian, not regional dialects
•  Medical/aesthetic terminology has well-established Russian equivalents
•  Brand names stay in English/Latin script (very common in Russian aesthetic medicine marketing)
•  Georgian personal names can be transliterated to Russian: \u041D\u0438\u043D\u043E, \u041A\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043D, \u041C\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043C, \u0421\u043E\u0444\u0438\u044F
8.5 Turkish (tr)
•  LTR language using Latin script with Turkish-specific characters (\u00E7, \u011F, \u0131, \u00F6, \u015F, \u00FC)
•  Use standard Istanbul Turkish, not regional dialects
•  Medical/aesthetic terminology often uses international terms adapted to Turkish phonology
•  Brand names stay in English/Latin script
•  Some aesthetic terms have well-established Turkish equivalents (e.g., cilt gen\u00E7le\u015Ftirme = skin rejuvenation)
